{{Infobox language |name=Cibak |nativename=Kyibaku |states=[[Nigeria]] |region=[[Borno State]] |speakers=200,000 |date=2014 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Chadic languages|Chadic]] |fam3=[[Biu–Mandara languages|Biu–Mandara]] |fam4=Bura–Higi |fam5=[[Bura languages|Bura]] (A.2) |iso3=ckl |glotto=ciba1236 |glottorefname=Cibak |lingua=18-GBB-a }}
'''Cibak''' (variously rendered ''Chibuk, Chibok, Chibbak, Chibbuk, Kyibaku, Kibbaku, Kikuk'') is an [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] language spoken by about 200,000 people in Nigeria.<ref name=e18/>
Cibak is spoken in [[Askira/Uba]], [[Chibok]] and [[Damboa]] local government areas in the south of [[Borno State]] in Nigeria.<ref>http://1verse.com/files/Kibaku-2009_05.pdf{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The majority of speakers are Christian;<ref>{{cite web|title=Kibaku of Nigeria|work=Prayer Focus|publisher=The Seed Company|url=http://www.theseedcompany.org/story/kibaku-nigeria|accessdate=May 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517153124/http://www.theseedcompany.org/story/kibaku-nigeria|archive-date=May 17, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> most of the schoolgirls abducted in the [[2014 Chibok kidnapping]] by Boko Haram were Cibak-speakers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tales of Escapees in Nigeria Add to Worries About Other Kidnapped Girls|date=May 14, 2014|work=New York Times|author=Adam Nossiter|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/15/world/africa/tales-of-escapees-in-nigeria-add-to-worries-about-other-kidnapped-girls.html|accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref>
