A '''style tribe''' or '''fashion tribe''' is a group of people that [[clothing|dress]] in a distinctive style to show their membership in this group.<ref name=wwd>[http://www.wwd.com/dictionary/fashion#fashiontribes Women's Wear Daily fashion dictionary]</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A04E7D61639F934A35752C1A961958260|title=Invoking Tribal Spirits as 90's Muses|author=Constance C. R. White|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=1997-10-07}}</ref> Examples include [[punk fashion|punks]], [[goth fashion|goths]], [[hip-hop fashion|hip-hop devotees]], and [[rave]]rs.<ref name=wwd/> The term "style tribe" appears to have been coined by [[anthropologist]] [[Ted Polhemus]], who analyzed style tribes in terms of the modern primitive and an abandonment of a linear trajectory of progress in fashion.<ref name=wwd/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19961109/ai_n14080388 | title=Books: Pinned and wriggling | newspaper = Independent, The (London)}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>Maynard, Margaret. ''Dress and Globalisation''. Manchester University Press (2004), [https://books.google.com/books?id=bkWIHaI1mfsC&pg=PA122&sig=camZ6Ldk9CyEnbxoz5YZH893kfI p122]. {{ISBN|0-7190-6389-2}}.</ref><ref>Margry, Peter Jan & Herman Roodenburg. ''Reframing Dutch Culture: Between Otherness and Authenticity''. Ashgate Publishing (2007), [https://books.google.com/books?id=PG53jNVPMFQC&pg=PA13&sig=0dLJ9xMOEw24_sCbYq_hl8gBGk8 p13]. {{ISBN|0-7546-4705-6}}.</ref>
